llm_answer:
The vapor pressure of the solution is related to the mole fraction of benzene by Raoult’s law:

\[
P_{\text{solution}} = x_{\text{benzene}}\;P^{\circ}_{\text{benzene}}
\]

Hence

\[
x_{\text{benzene}}=\frac{P_{\text{solution}}}{P^{\circ}_{\text{benzene}}
}= \frac{51.5}{53.3}=0.966
\]

For a non‑volatile solute

\[
x_{\text{benzene}}=\frac{n_{\text{benzene}}}{n_{\text{benzene}}+n_{\text{solute}}}
\]

The number of moles of benzene in 500 g is

\[
n_{\text{benzene}}=\frac{500\;\text{g}}{78.11\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}=6.399\;\text{mol}
\]

Solve for \(n_{\text{solute}}\):

\[
0.966=\frac{6.399}{6.399+n_{\text{solute}}}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
n_{\text{solute}}=\frac{6.399(1-0.966)}{0.966}=0.225\;\text{mol}
\]

The solute mass is 19.0 g, so its molar mass \(M\) is

\[
M=\frac{19.0\;\text{g}}{0.225\;\text{mol}}=84.4\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{84.4}\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

