llm_answer:
The freezing‑point depression is  

\[
\Delta T_f = T_f^{\text{pure water}}-T_f^{\text{solution}}
           = 0^\circ\text{C}-(-1.12^\circ\text{C}) = 1.12^\circ\text{C}
\]

For water, the cryoscopic constant is \(K_f = 1.86^\circ\text{C}\,\text{kg mol}^{-1}\).

\[
m = \frac{\Delta T_f}{K_f}
   = \frac{1.12}{1.86}\;\text{mol kg}^{-1}
   \approx 0.602\;\text{mol kg}^{-1}
\]

The solvent mass is \(1000\;\text{g}=1\;\text{kg}\), so the number of moles of solute is

\[
n = m \times 1\;\text{kg} \approx 0.602\;\text{mol}
\]

The solute mass is \(100\;\text{g}\).  
Hence the molar mass \(M\) is

\[
M = \frac{\text{mass}}{n}
  = \frac{100\;\text{g}}{0.602\;\text{mol}}
  \approx 1.66\times10^{2}\;\text{g mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{166}\text{ Da}
\]

