The mass fractions give the relative amounts of each component.  
Assume 100 g of membrane:

- Protein: \(75\;\text{g}\)  
- Lipid: \(25\;\text{g}\)

Moles of each component  

\[
n_{\text{protein}}=\frac{75\;\text{g}}{26\,000\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}
=2.88\times10^{-3}\;\text{mol}
\]

\[
n_{\text{lipid}}=\frac{25\;\text{g}}{800\;\text{g mol}^{-1}}
=3.125\times10^{-2}\;\text{mol}
\]

Mole ratio (lipid : protein)

\[
\frac{n_{\text{lipid}}}{n_{\text{protein}}}
=\frac{3.125\times10^{-2}}{2.88\times10^{-3}}
\approx 10.8
\]

Thus the phospholipid to protein mole ratio is about **11 : 1**.

\[
\boxed{11:1}
\]

