\]

To keep the ionic product below \(K_{sp}\) the hydroxide concentration must satisfy  

\[
[\ce{OH^-}]_{\text{max}}=\sqrt{\frac{K_{sp}}{[\ce{Mg^{2+}}]}}
=\sqrt{\frac{5.62\times10^{-12}}{0.05}}
=1.06\times10^{-5}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}
\]

Adding \(\ce{NH4Cl}\) supplies \(\ce{NH4^+}\) which reacts with \(\ce{OH^-}\) according to  

\[
\ce{NH4^+ + OH^- \rightleftharpoons NH3 + H2O}\qquad K'=\frac{1}{K_b}=5.56\times10^{4}
\]

Using the equilibrium condition  

\[
K'=\frac{[\ce{NH3}]}{[\ce{NH4^+}][\ce{OH^-}]}
\]

and the fact that the final \([\ce{NH3}]\approx0.050\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}\), we obtain  

\[
[\ce{NH4^+}]_{\text{final}}=\frac{0.050}{5.56\times10^{4}\times1.06\times10^{-5}}
=8.49\times10^{-2}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}
\]

The initial \([\ce{NH4^+}]\) from hydrolysis is \(1.06\times10^{-5}\ \text{mol dm}^{-3}\); therefore the amount of \(\ce{NH4Cl}\) that must be added to reach the required \([\ce{NH4^+}]\) is  

\[
n_{\ce{NH4Cl}}=\bigl(8.49\times10^{-2}-1.06\times10^{-5}\bigr)\times0.20
=1.70\times10^{-2}\ \text{mol}
\]

Finally, the mass of \(\ce{NH4Cl}\) needed is  

\[
m_{\ce{NH4Cl}}=n_{\ce{NH4Cl}}\times M_{\ce{NH4Cl}}
=1.70\times10^{-2}\ \text{mol}\times53.5\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
=0.91\ \text{g}
\]

