llm_answer:
The overall reaction can be written as the sum of the dissolution of \(\ce{CuCl}\) and the reduction of \(\ce{Cu^+}\):

\[
\ce{CuCl(s) -> Cu^+ + Cl^-}\qquad K_{\text{sp}}=1.7\times10^{-7}
\]

\[
\ce{Cu^+ + e^- -> Cu(s)}\qquad E^{\ominus}=0.52\ \text{V}
\]

The Gibbs free‑energy change for the dissolution is

\[
\Delta G_{\text{diss}}^{\ominus} = -RT\ln K_{\text{sp}}
\]

and for the reduction

\[
\Delta G_{\text{red}}^{\ominus} = -nFE^{\ominus} = -F(0.52\ \text{V})\quad (n=1)
\]

Adding the two gives the overall \(\Delta G^{\ominus}\):

\[
\Delta G_{\text{overall}}^{\ominus}
= -F(0.52\ \text{V}) - RT\ln K_{\text{sp}}
\]

The standard potential for the overall reaction is

\[
E_{\text{overall}}^{\ominus}
= -\frac{\Delta G_{\text{overall}}^{\ominus}}{nF}
= 0.52\ \text{V} + \frac{RT}{F}\ln K_{\text{sp}}
\]

At \(25^{\circ}\text{C}\), \(RT/F = 0.025693\ \text{V}\) and

\[
\ln K_{\text{sp}} = \ln(1.7\times10^{-7}) = -15.5875
\]

Hence

\[
E_{\text{overall}}^{\ominus}
= 0.52\ \text{V} + 0.025693\ \text{V}\times(-15.5875)
= 0.52\ \text{V} - 0.400\ \text{V}
\approx 0.12\ \text{V}
\]

\[
\boxed{0.12}\ \text{V}
\]

