llm_answer:
The hydrolysis of the conjugate base \(X^{-}\) gives

\[
X^{-}+H_{2}O \rightleftharpoons HX+OH^{-}
\]

With an initial concentration of \(X^{-}\) of \(0.20\;\text{mol dm}^{-3}\) and a measured pH of 9, the hydroxide concentration is

\[
pOH = 14-9 = 5 \quad\Rightarrow\quad [OH^-] = 10^{-5}\;\text{mol dm}^{-3}
\]

At equilibrium \( [OH^-] = [HX] = 10^{-5}\;\text{mol dm}^{-3}\) and \( [X^-] \approx 0.20\;\text{mol dm}^{-3}\).

Thus the base‑dissociation constant is

\[
K_b = \frac{[HX][OH^-]}{[X^-]}
      = \frac{(10^{-5})(10^{-5})}{0.20}
      = 5\times10^{-10}
\]

The acid dissociation constant is related by \(K_a K_b = K_w = 1.0\times10^{-14}\):

\[
K_a = \frac{K_w}{K_b}
     = \frac{1.0\times10^{-14}}{5\times10^{-10}}
     = 2\times10^{-5}
\]

\[
\boxed{2\times10^{-5}}
\]

