llm_answer:
The effective permeability‑to‑thickness ratio for the coated membrane is obtained by adding the resistances of the skin and the silicone coating in series.  
For the polysulfone skin

\[
\left(\frac{P}{\ell}\right)_{\text{skin,CO}_2}
   =\frac{P_{\text{skin,CO}_2}\,(A_3/A_2)}{\ell_{\text{skin}}}
   =\frac{2000\;\text{Barrer}\times1.9\times10^{-6}}{1.0\times10^{-4}\;\text{cm}}
   \approx 3.8\times10^{1}\;\text{Barrer/cm}
\]

For the silicone coating

\[
\left(\frac{P}{\ell}\right)_{\text{coat,CO}_2}
   =\frac{P_{\text{coat,CO}_2}}{\ell_{\text{coat}}}
   =\frac{2000\;\text{Barrer}}{1.0\times10^{-4}\;\text{cm}}
   \approx 2.0\times10^{7}\;\text{Barrer/cm}
\]

The overall resistance is dominated by the skin, so

\[
\boxed{\left(\frac{P}{\ell}\right)_{\text{eff,CO}_2}\approx 3.8\times10^{1}\;\text{Barrer/cm}}
\]

For the permselectivity, the same procedure is applied to CH\(_4\) (using \(P_{\text{skin,CH}_4}=200\) Barrer and \(P_{\text{coat,CH}_4}=200\) Barrer):

\[
\left(\frac{P}{\ell}\right)_{\text{eff,CH}_4}\approx 3.8\;\text{Barrer/cm}
\]

Hence the effective permselectivity of the coated membrane is

\[
\boxed{\alpha_{\text{CO}_2/\text{CH}_4}
      =\frac{(P/\ell)_{\text{eff,CO}_2}}
             {(P/\ell)_{\text{eff,CH}_4}}
      \approx \frac{38}{3.8}\approx 1.0\times10^{1}}
\]

