llm_answer:
The power \(P\) released by a fuel under the same pressure is proportional to the magnitude of its standard enthalpy of combustion \(|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}|\) and inversely proportional to the square root of its relative molecular mass \(M\):

\[
P \propto \frac{|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}|}{\sqrt{M}}
\]

Hence the ratio of the powers for hydrogen and methane is

\[
\frac{P_{\ce{H2}}}{P_{\ce{CH4}}}
= \frac{|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}(\ce{H2})|/\sqrt{M_{\ce{H2}}}}
       {|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}(\ce{CH4})|/\sqrt{M_{\ce{CH4}}}}
\]

Insert the given values:

\[
\begin{aligned}
|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}(\ce{H2})| &= 285.8\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1} \\
|\Delta H^\circ_{\text{comb}}(\ce{CH4})| &= 890.3\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1} \\
M_{\ce{H2}} &= 2.016\ \text{g mol}^{-1} \\
M_{\ce{CH4}} &= 16.04\ \text{g mol}^{-1}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{P_{\ce{H2}}}{P_{\ce{CH4}}}
&= \frac{285.8/\sqrt{2.016}}{890.3/\sqrt{16.04}} \\
&= \frac{285.8/1.420}{890.3/4.005} \\
&= \frac{201.3}{222.5} \\
&\approx 0.904
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
\boxed{0.904}
\]

