llm_answer:
The rotational partition function for a linear molecule is  

\[
q_{\text{rot}}=\frac{kT}{\sigma\,h c B}
\]

where \(B\) is the rotational constant in \(\text{cm}^{-1}\) and \(\sigma\) is the symmetry number (\(\sigma=2\) for \(\ce{CO2}\)).  

At \(T=298\;\text{K}\):

\[
kT = (1.380649\times10^{-23}\,\text{J K}^{-1})(298\,\text{K}) = 4.112\times10^{-21}\,\text{J}
\]

\[
h c = (6.62607015\times10^{-34}\,\text{J s})(2.99792458\times10^{10}\,\text{cm s}^{-1}) = 1.98644586\times10^{-23}\,\text{J cm}
\]

\[
h c B = (1.98644586\times10^{-23}\,\text{J cm})(0.3902\,\text{cm}^{-1}) = 7.756\times10^{-24}\,\text{J}
\]

\[
q_{\text{rot}} = \frac{4.112\times10^{-21}}{2(7.756\times10^{-24})}=2.65\times10^{2}
\]

The rotational contribution to the molar Gibbs free energy is

\[
G_{\text{rot}} = -RT\ln q_{\text{rot}}
\]

\[
RT = (8.314462618\,\text{J mol}^{-1}\text{K}^{-1})(298\,\text{K}) = 2.478\times10^{3}\,\text{J mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\ln q_{\text{rot}} = \ln(2.65\times10^{2}) = 5.579
\]

\[
G_{\text{rot}} = -(2.478\times10^{3})(5.579)\,\text{J mol}^{-1}
          = -1.381\times10^{4}\,\text{J mol}^{-1}
          = -13.8\,\text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\boxed{-13.8}\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}
\]

